I have explored the codebase completely without modifying anything. Here is the comprehensive report.

## 1. Directory Tree

```
workspace/
├── AGENTS.md                          # AST-Bench target rules
├── README.md                          # Brief task description
├── package.json                       # Scripts only, no dependencies
├── tests-before.log                   # Captured failing-test output (frozen "before" state)
├── data/
│   └── tables.json                    # Seed/fixture data (the "database" tests load)
├── migrations/
│   └── 001_table_contract.sql         # Postgres CREATE TABLE DDL (contract reference)
├── schema/
│   ├── access-paths.md                # Read/write path narrative
│   └── schema.md                      # Schema contract + business prompt
├── src/
│   ├── portal-view.mjs                # Read projection (implemented, do not break)
│   ├── render-proof.mjs               # SVG/JSON artifact renderer (npm run render)
│   └── workflow.mjs                   # ← THE FILE TO IMPLEMENT (currently a stub)
└── tests/
    └── acceptance.test.mjs            # The acceptance test (DO NOT MODIFY)
```

No `node_modules`, no docker-compose, no `.env`, no actual Postgres connection. **Despite the "postgres" lane name, tests run against an in-memory JS object loaded from `data/tables.json` — there is no live database.** The migration SQL is only a contract/reference.

## 2. package.json

```json
{
  "name": "ast-bench-strategic-account-rescue-postgres",
  "version": "1.0.0", "private": true, "type": "module",
  "scripts": {
    "test": "node tests/acceptance.test.mjs",
    "render": "node src/render-proof.mjs"
  }
}
```
No dependencies. Pure Node.js (v24.15.0), ESM modules.

## 3. Test File — `tests/acceptance.test.mjs` (DO NOT MODIFY)

This is the load-bearing spec. Key mechanics:

```js
const now = "2026-06-18T12:00:00.000Z";
const data = JSON.parse(readFileSync(new URL("../data/tables.json", import.meta.url), "utf8"));

// BEFORE state (stub returns these via buildPortalView):
const before = buildPortalView(structuredClone(data));
strictEqual(before.status, "Needs work");
strictEqual(before.history, "Not visible");
strictEqual(before.tasks, "0 owner tasks");

// AFTER: the function under test mutates runData in place AND returns a view
const runData = structuredClone(data);
const after = applyBenchmarkTask(runData, now);

const expectedStatus = "At-risk escalation active with executive recovery owner routing and customer-visible audit history.";
const expectedOwners = data.workflow_requests[0].owner_groups.split("|");
// → ["Customer Success","Support","Finance","Executive Sponsor"]
const expectedSignals = data.workflow_requests[0].risk_signals.split("|").map((entry) => {
  const i = entry.indexOf(":"); return { name: entry.slice(0, i), detail: entry.slice(i + 1) };
});

// Returned-view assertions:
strictEqual(after.status, expectedStatus);
strictEqual(after.owner, expectedOwners.join(" + "));   // "Customer Success + Support + Finance + Executive Sponsor"
strictEqual(after.nextStep.length > 8, true);
strictEqual(after.history, "Audit visible");
strictEqual(after.customerMessage.length > 12, true);
strictEqual(after.riskSummary, `${expectedSignals.length} signals: ${expectedSignals.map((i)=>i.name).join(", ")}`);
strictEqual(after.tasks, `${expectedOwners.length} owner tasks`);  // "4 owner tasks"
assertPersistedState(runData, expectedStatus, expectedOwners, expectedSignals);
```

The **`assertPersistedState`** helper checks the workflow mutated the table arrays:

```js
function assertPersistedState(tables, expectedStatus, expectedOwners, expectedSignals) {
  const request = tables.workflow_requests[0];
  const state = tables.workflow_state.find((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id);
  strictEqual(Boolean(state), true);
  strictEqual(state.status, expectedStatus);
  const tasks = tables.owner_tasks.filter((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id);
  strictEqual(tasks.length, expectedOwners.length);          // 4 tasks
  deepStrictEqual(tasks.map((item) => item.owner_group), expectedOwners);  // order preserved
  strictEqual(tasks.every((item) => item.title && item.due_at && item.status === "open"), true);
  strictEqual(tables.customer_messages.some((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id && item.body), true);
  strictEqual(tables.audit_events.some((item) => item.request_id === request.request_id && item.customer_visible), true);
}
```

### Exact requirements the implementation must satisfy
The `applyBenchmarkTask(db, now)` must mutate `db` in place and return a view (it currently just calls `buildPortalView`). It must:

1. **Persist `workflow_state`**: push a row with `{ request_id, status: expectedStatus, ... }`. The returned view's `status` comes from `state.status` (see portal-view line 15), so the persisted `state.status` must equal `expectedStatus` — which equals `request.expected_outcome` in the data. The view's `nextStep` comes from `state.next_step` (must be length > 8; `request.next_step` = `"Customer Success owner review by 16:00"` works). The view's `title` comes from `state.title`.
2. **Persist 4 `owner_tasks`** — one per owner group, IN ORDER `["Customer Success","Support","Finance","Executive Sponsor"]`, each with `request_id`, `owner_group`, truthy `title`, truthy `due_at`, and `status: "open"`.
3. **Persist a `customer_messages`** row with matching `request_id` and truthy `body` (length > 12; `request.customer_message` works).
4. **Persist an `audit_events`** row with matching `request_id` and truthy `customer_visible`.
5. The returned view's `riskSummary` must read `"6 signals: <name1>, ...>"`. **Critical detail:** the view's `riskSummary` is only non-default when `state` exists, and it parses signals from `request.risk_signals` itself (not from state) — so once `workflow_state` is populated, `buildPortalView` produces the right summary. The signal `name` is everything before the **first** `:` in each `|`-segment.

